You're absolutely right: many real-time chat apps (like Telegram Web or WhatsApp Web) donâ€™t use URL routing for each user. Instead, they keep everything on one page and use state to determine which chat is active.

So your app likely works like this:

Left side: list of users or chats.

Right side: shows messages based on the currently selected user stored in React state.

No route change happens when selecting a user.

âœ… So... is it possible to switch to User B's chat on notification click?
Yes, it's 100% possible â€” but you need to make sure that:

The notification click triggers a state update.

That state tells your app to switch to User Bâ€™s chat.

ðŸ”§ How to implement it
Hereâ€™s the key idea:

Your app has some global state (React Context, Redux, Zustand, or even lifting state up) that tracks the current chat user.

When a notification is clicked, you dispatch an event or call a function to update that state with User Bâ€™s ID.

âœ… Example Using React Context
Assume you have a ChatContext that holds:

js
Copy
Edit
const [selectedUserId, setSelectedUserId] = useState(null);
In your notification code:

js
Copy
Edit
const notifyUser = (senderId, senderName) => {
  if (Notification.permission === "granted") {
    const notification = new Notification(`New message from ${senderName}`, {
      body: "Click to view chat",
      icon: "/chat-icon.png"
    });

    notification.onclick = () => {
      window.focus();

      // Custom event to tell React to switch chat
      const event = new CustomEvent("switch-to-user", { detail: { userId: senderId } });
      window.dispatchEvent(event);
    };
  }
};
Then, in your React app (maybe in App.jsx or wherever your context/state is defined):

js
Copy
Edit
useEffect(() => {
  const handler = (e) => {
    const userId = e.detail.userId;
    setSelectedUserId(userId); // Now chat UI will show messages with this user
  };

  window.addEventListener("switch-to-user", handler);
  return () => window.removeEventListener("switch-to-user", handler);
}, []);
ðŸ§  Key Points
This is very close to how desktop chat apps handle this.

You don't need URL changes â€” just listen to events and update state.

You can also use global state tools (Redux, Zustand, etc.) if preferred.

